SIMPLE: espouse
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Espouse
<hw>Es*pouse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Espoused</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Espousing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>espouser</ets>, <ets>esposer</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pouser</ets>,
L. <ets>sponsare</ets> to betroth, espouse, fr. <ets>sponsus</ets>
betrothed, p. p. of <ets>spondere</ets> to promise solemnly or sacredly.
Cf. <er>Spouse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To betroth; to promise in
marriage; to give as spouse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A virgin <qex>espoused</qex> to a man whose name was Joseph.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke i. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take as spouse; to take to wife; to
marry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lavinia will I make my empress, . . . ⟦br⟧
And in the sacred Pantheon her <qex>espouse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take to one's self with a view to maintain; to
make one's own; to take up the cause of; to adopt; to embrace.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>espoused</xex> that quarrel.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Promised faithfully to <qex>espouse</qex> his cause as soon as he
got out of the war.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Espousement</ent>⟦br⟧
